<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-651-774  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 651 774.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>The New York Times  Sept 17 1989 v138 pF11(W) pF11(E) 21 col in.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Beware those network failures: local area networks are spreading,but system failures can be costly. (The Executive Computer)(column)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Lewis, Peter H.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Local area network (LAN) failures are a larger problem than mostpeople think, costing a large corporation an average of $3.48million in losses per year, with an average of 23.6 networkfailures a year.andP;  Each failure averages 4.9 hours, according to astudy by Infonetics Inc, a market research and consulting firmspecializing in computer networking issues.andP;  Networks fail forsimple reasons, such as an employee who accidentally plugs thewrong diskette into a microcomputer.andP;  More commonly, networks failbecause more businesses are buying their networking products froma variety of vendors, often leading to a clash of protocols,operating systems and other functions.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Company:   Infonetics Inc. (research).andO;Topic:     Local area networks (Computer networks)StudyNetwork Management.andO;Feature:   illustrationcartoon.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>